Days of the week

are there some days of the week where more accidents happen than on others (use variable DAY_WEEK)? Assuming 1 is Sunday, it looks like accidents are increased on the weekends, and lower towards the middle of the week.

ggplot(accident_filter, aes(x=DAY_WEEK) ) + geom_histogram() 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Time of the day

what time of the day do accidents happen (use variable HOUR)? there is a small increase in accidents in the morning as people drive to work and a larger hump from noon to midnight with a peak at 5 in the afternoon as people drive home from work.

accident_filter = dplyr::filter(accident_filter, HOUR<25)
ggplot(accident_filter, aes(x=HOUR) ) + geom_histogram(binwidth=1)

Drunk Driving

what is the number of accidents with at least one drunk driver (use variable DRUNK_DR)? 8,720 accidents with at least one drunk driver

ggplot(accident, aes(x=DRUNK_DR) ) + geom_histogram()

Connecting Person and Accident

Connect to the person table. Identify drivers (PER_TYP == 1, see fars manual ) and subset on them.

Join accident and driver table (work out which variable(s) to use)

Tally the number of accidents by day of the week (DAY_WEEK), hour of the day (HOUR) and gender (SEX). Visualize the results!

drivers = dplyr::filter(person, PER_TYP == 1)
combo_data = left_join(accident, drivers, by="ST_CASE")


ggplot(combo_data, aes(x=DAY_WEEK) ) + geom_bar() +
geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust=-1)
## Warning: The dot-dot notation (`..count..`) was deprecated in ggplot2 3.4.0.
## ℹ Please use `after_stat(count)` instead.

combo_data_filter = dplyr::filter(combo_data, HOUR.x<25)
ggplot(combo_data_filter, aes(x=HOUR.x) ) + geom_bar()+
geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust=-1)

combo_data_filter2 = dplyr::filter(combo_data, SEX<3)
ggplot(combo_data_filter2, aes(x=SEX)) + geom_bar()+
geom_text(stat='count', aes(label=..count..), vjust=-1)
